		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">That's what I meant by "And both kinds of cards make money on the merchant fee."</div><br />Here in Brazil, small stores (mostly the ones selling computer parts and video game consoles) offer a discount if you pay in cash, since they don't have to pay card taxes in this case. Big stores don't have that, and their prices are higher anyway (A Wii, for example, costs US$500 in a big store, while a modded one costs US$420 in a small store - still over twice what it costs in the US, insane isn't it?).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">If your debit card has embossed numbers on the front and says "VISA" or "MasterCard" then it should work for any merchant that takes VISA or MasterCard cards. The PayPal debit card, for instance, has a MasterCard logo.</div>
<br />Yeah, my card is like that. When I use my debit card "manually" I have to input a code into their machine thingy, how does that work online? Can they charge whatever they want just based on your card's number? This was scary enough with credit cards, but when the money comes off straight from your bank account it's even scarier.

		

