		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Here in Brazil, small stores (mostly the ones selling computer parts and video game consoles) offer a discount if you pay in cash, since they don't have to pay card taxes in this case.</div><br />In the United States, on the other hand, retail merchants that take VISA or MasterCard don't give a discount for paying with cash vs. paying with plastic.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">(A Wii, for example, costs US$500 in a big store, while a modded one costs US$420 in a small store - still over twice what it costs in the US, insane isn't it?).</div><br />Then vote the overtaxing illegitimates out of office. Has the government of Brazil ever given a straight answer as to the reason for the high tariff on imported consumer electronics? It'd be one thing if Brazil didn't have an income tax and relied on VAT.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">When I use my debit card "manually" I have to input a code into their machine thingy, how does that work online?</div><br />It doesn't. Swipe + PIN is through the ATM network; swipe + signature is through the credit card network.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Can they charge whatever they want just based on your card's number?</div>
<br />Yes. Banks aren't required to give as much fraud protection for debit card purchases as for credit card purchases, but they typically do to attract customers.

		

